orce%20with%20massive%20shore%20bombardment%20and%20calls%20for%20immediate%20direct%20fire.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhat%20the%20Navy%20could%20really%20use%20for%20these%20operations%20is%20a%20new%20version%20of%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.history.navy.mil%2Fresearch%2Fhistories%2Fship-histories%2Fdanfs%2Fw%2Fwhite-ri.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EUSS%20White%20River%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20a%20unique%20yet%20little-known%20ship%20that%20served%20as%20a%20workhorse%20for%20the%20US%20Navy%20in%20two%20wars.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDesigned%20from%20a%20landing%20ship%20meant%20to%20drop%20troops%20and%20supplies%20off%20at%20beachheads%2C%20the%20USS%20White%20River's%2025%20years%20of%20service%20didn't%20see%20the%20ship%20drop%20off%20a%20single%20soldier%20or%20vehicle%20into%20combat.%20Instead%2C%20the%20ship%20acted%20as%20a%20floating%20battery%2C%20raining%20hundreds%20of%20thousands%20of%20rockets%2C%20mortars%2C%20and%20gun%20rounds%20on%20enemy%20targets.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIts%20deployment%20into%20any%20given%20area%20always%20raised%20the%20morale%20of%20the%20soldiers%20it%20supported%2C%20wrought%20havoc%20on%20entire%20enemy%20units%2C%20and%20demonstrated%20the%20importance%20of%20naval%20fire%20support.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMore%20than%20half%20a%20century%20after%20the%20White%20River's%20decommissioning%2C%20the%20US%20Navy%20is%20looking%20to%20build%20a%20new%20generation%20of%20medium-sized%20landing%20ships%2C%20some%20of%20which%20could%20become%20modern%20versions%20of%20the%20White%20River.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Rows%20of%20rockets%20were%20set%20up%20on%20an%20LSMR-188-class%20ship%2C%20the%20forerunner%20to%20the%20White%20River's%20class%2C%20around%201945.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F66e1b29aa0ff598b26667f10%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%222440%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3ERows%20of%20rockets%20were%20set%20up%20on%20an%20LSMR-188-class%20ship%2C%20the%20forerunner%20to%20the%20White%20River's%20class%2C%20around%201945.%3Cp%3ENational%20Archives%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22fd328ec9-a3b7-4b92-b07d-2e2c9359787f%5C%22%3E'Rocket%20ships'%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EUSS%20White%20River's%20design%20was%20the%20product%20of%20an%20evolving%20way%20to%20address%20the%20needs%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.usni.org%2Fmagazines%2Fproceedings%2F1945%2Fnovember%2Fnaval-gunfire-scourge-beaches%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eshore%20bombardment%20during%20World%20War%20II%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAllied%20assaults%20on%20the%20beaches%20of%20the%20Pacific%2C%20Africa%2C%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fd-day-largest-last-amphibious-invasion-2024-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EEurope%3C%2Fa%3E%20had%20proved%20the%20need%20for%20massive%20firepower%20to%20destroy%20fortified%20fighting%20positions%20and%20minefields.%20The%20deck%20guns%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Flast-remaining-us-navy-battleships-now-serving-as-museums-2024-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ebattleships%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20cruisers%2C%20and%20even%20destroyers%20were%20sometimes%20too%20slow%20to%20provide%20accurate%20fire%20or%20too%20powerful%20in%20the%20immediacy%20of%20troop%20landings.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20best%20solution%20was%2C%20for%20lack%20of%20a%20better%20term%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.usni.org%2Fmagazines%2Fnaval-history-magazine%2F2021%2Fjune%2Frocket-ships%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erocket%20ships%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cu%3E%3A%3C%2Fu%3E%20Small%20vessels%20porcupined%20with%20rocket%20launchers%20able%20to%20fire%20dozens%20or%20even%20thousands%20of%20rockets%20en%20masse.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERather%20than%20building%20an%20entirely%20new%20vessel%2C%20it%20was%20decided%20to%20modify%20medium-sized%20landing%20ships%20(classified%20as%20LSMs%20for%20'Landing%20Ship%20Medium').%20Originally%20designed%20to%20carry%20troops%2C%20vehicles%2C%20and%20supplies%20directly%20onto%20beachheads%2C%20the%20vessels%20proved%20to%20be%20quite%20versatile%2C%20with%20many%20models%20being%20reconfigured%20for%20various%20uses.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EGiven%20the%20designation%20%26quot%3BLSMR%26quot%3B%20for%20%26quot%3BLanding%20Ship%20Medium%20%E2%80%93%20Rocket%2C%26quot%3B%20their%20size%20and%20cargo%20space%20enabled%20the%20ships%20to%20carry%20thousands%20of%20rockets%20at%20a%20time%2C%20and%20their%20shallow%20draft%20enabled%20them%20to%20sail%20up%20to%20the%20shore%2C%20giving%20them%20the%20ability%20to%20fire%20rockets%20further%20inland.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20first%20rocket%20fire%20support%20ships%20the%20US%20Navy%20operated%2C%20like%20the%20British-made%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.combinedops.com%2FUS%2520LANDING%2520CRAFT%2520ROCKET.htm%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ELanding%20Craft%20Tank%20(Rocket)%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.navsource.org%2Farchives%2F10%2F06%2F06188.htm%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ELSMR-188-class%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20though%20useful%2C%20had%20issues%20that%20hampered%20their%20effectiveness.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAlthough%20equipped%20with%20thousands%20of%20rockets%2C%20the%20launchers%20were%20welded%20in%20place%20facing%20forward%2C%20forcing%20the%20ship%20to%20point%20towards%20its%20target%20for%20all%20salvos%20%E2%80%94%20a%20difficult%20task%20in%20high%20winds%2C%20changing%20tides%2C%20or%20choppy%20seas.%20Additionally%2C%20it%20took%20hours%20to%20reload%20all%20of%20the%20launchers%20for%20a%20full%20salvo%2C%20and%20the%20crew%20had%20to%20be%20confined%20below%20deck%20during%20firing%2C%20as%20the%20exhaust%20from%20the%20rockets%20was%20toxic.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20solutions%20were%20the%20LSMR-401%20and%20follow-on%20LSMR-501-classes%3B%20these%20designs%20modified%20from%20the%20LSMR-188%20featured%20a%20better%20layout%20%E2%80%94%20the%20superstructure%20housing%20the%20bridge%2C%20for%20example%2C%20was%20moved%20aft%20and%20the%205-inch%20gun%20turret%20placed%20directly%20in%20front%20of%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20armament%20was%20also%20further%20upgraded%2C%20with%20two%2040mm%20and%20four%2020mm%20anti-aircraft%20guns%20(which%20could%20be%20pointed%20horizontally%20to%20fire%20at%20land-based%20targets)%2C%20four%204-inch%20mortars%2C%20and%2C%20depending%20on%20the%20layout%2C%20eight%20to%20ten%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.military.com%2Fvideo%2Frockets%2Fartillery-rockets%2Fnavy-automatic-rocket-artillery-1942%2F2536439296001%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EMark%20102%3C%2Fa%3E%20double-barreled%20rocket%20launchers.%20The%20LSMR-501%20class's%20armament%20was%20slightly%20larger%2C%20with%20four%2040mm%20and%20eight%2020mm%20anti-aircraft%20guns.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20cornerstone%20of%20the%20ships'%20armament%2C%20the%20Mark%20102%20rocket%20launcher%2C%20fired%20two%205.0-inch%20spin-stabilized%20rockets%20within%20one%20second%2C%20after%20which%20it%20was%20automatically%20reloaded%20within%20three%20seconds%2C%20enabling%20each%20launcher%20to%20fire%20about%2030%20rockets%20per%20minute%20%E2%80%94%20a%20blistering%20rate%20for%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fnew-european-europuls-rocket-launcher-could-rival-himars-2024-7%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erocket%20artillery%20systems%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFour%20types%20of%20rockets%20could%20be%20fired%2C%20with%20warheads%20ranging%20from%201.7%20to%2012%20pounds%20and%20ranges%20of%201.4%20to%205.6%20miles.%20Depending%20on%20the%20makeup%20of%20the%20loadout%2C%20a%20ship%20could%20carry%20anywhere%20from%201%2C500%20to%205%2C000%20rockets.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20destructive%20potential%20of%20a%20single%20LSMR-401%2F501-class%20ship%20was%20large%20enough%20that%20the%20Navy%20boasted%20that%20it%20had%20as%20much%20firepower%20as%20five%20destroyers.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20USS%20Des%20Plaines%20River%2C%20one%20of%20the%20other%20landing%20ships%20upgraded%20to%20fire%20rockets.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F66e1b37da0ff598b26667f71%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221600%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20USS%20Des%20Plaines%20River%2C%20one%20of%20the%20other%20landing%20ships%20upgraded%20to%20fire%20rockets.%3Cp%3ENational%20Archives%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22a3cc23fe-7ed0-4d29-a6c4-81c6f7bd923d%5C%22%3EIn%20action%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ELaid%20down%20in%20June%20of%201945%2C%20USS%20White%20River%20was%20one%20of%2036%20ships%20of%20the%20LSMR-501-class%2C%20and%20originally%20only%20referred%20to%20by%20its%20hull%20number%2C%20LSMR-536.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ELaunched%20on%20July%2014%20and%20commissioned%20on%20November%2028%2C%20the%20ship%2C%20like%20the%20rest%20of%20the%20vessels%20in%20its%20class%2C%20arrived%20too%20late%20for%20World%20War%20II.%20Absent%20hostilities%2C%20it%20was%20decommissioned%20less%20than%20a%20year%20later%20on%20July%2031%2C%201946%20and%20placed%20in%20the%20Atlantic%20Reserve%20Fleet.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERecommissioned%20on%20September%2016%2C%201950%20as%20a%20result%20of%20the%20outbreak%20of%20war%20on%20the%20Korean%20Peninsula%2C%20it%20was%20refitted%2C%20crewed%2C%20and%20joined%20the%20Pacific%20Fleet%20in%20early%201951.%20After%20training%20stints%20in%20California%20and%20Japan%2C%20LSMR-536%20arrived%20off%20North%20Korean-controlled%20island%20of%20Ch'o-do%20on%20July%2016%2C%201952.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20ship%20would%20patrol%20along%20the%20western%20North%20Korean%20coastline%20intermittently%20(in%20one%20case%20providing%20night%20illumination%20fire%20on%20Ch'o-do)%20for%20the%20remainder%20of%20the%20war's%20hostilities%2C%20and%20would%20also%20patrol%20the%20South%20Korean%20coast%20afterwards%20until%201954.%20Officially%20renamed%20USS%20White%20River%20in%201955%2C%20the%20ship%20was%20decommissioned%20again%20in%201956.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhite%20River%20would%20remain%20in%20the%20Pacific%20Reserve%20Fleet%20in%20San%20Diego%20for%20nine%20years%20until%20it%20was%20recommissioned%20again%20in%201965%2C%20this%20time%20for%20service%20in%20Vietnam%2C%20where%20it%20made%20a%20name%20for%20itself.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EArriving%20off%20South%20Vietnam's%20Qu%E1%BA%A3ng%20Ng%C3%A3i%20Province%20on%20May%2025%2C%201966%2C%20White%20River%20was%20immediately%20involved%20in%20shore%20bombardment%20that%20very%20day.%20Two%20days%20later%2C%20the%20ship%20provided%20fire%20support%20for%20South%20Vietnamese%20Army%20units%20(ARVN)%20operating%20in%20the%20vicinity%2C%20doing%20so%20intermittently%20for%20the%20next%20two%20months%20while%20also%20supporting%20three%20other%20US%20military%20operations%20in%20the%20area%2C%20including%20one%20involving%20an%20amphibious%20landing.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPart%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3D9U0Mex36J_4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EInshore%20Fire%20Support%20Division%2093%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20USS%20White%20River%20sailed%20all%20along%20South%20Vietnam%2C%20from%20the%20Vietnamese%20DMZ%20to%20the%20Cambodian%20border%20in%20the%20Gulf%20of%20Thailand.%20It%20was%20even%20able%20to%20sail%20inland%20up%20the%20Mekong%20River%20Delta%20%E2%80%94%20an%20area%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.usni.org%2Fmagazines%2Fnaval-history-magazine%2F1987%2Fapril%2Fwar-vietnams-shallows%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erife%20with%20Viet%20Cong%20strongholds%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%94%20because%20of%20its%20shallow%20draft.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOver%20the%20next%20four%20years%2C%20USS%20White%20River%20took%20part%20in%20at%20least%2011%20named%20operations%2C%20supported%20American%2C%20Australian%2C%20South%20Korean%2C%20and%20South%20Vietnamese%20soldiers%2C%20and%20was%20responsible%20for%20destroying%20hundreds%20of%20Viet%20Cong%20ammo%20dumps%2C%20bunkers%2C%20structures%2C%20and%20boats%20used%20by%20the%20guerrillas.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BA%20love%20affair%20developed%2C%20and%20advisers%20in%20the%20outposts%20told%20us%20they%20couldn't%20sleep%20at%20night%20unless%20we%20were%20there.%20It%20would%20take%20six%20destroyers%20to%20replace%20us%2C%26quot%3B%20Lt.%20Cmdr.%20Roy%20E.%20McCoy%2C%20the%20commander%20of%20Inshore%20Fire%20Support%20Division%2093%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2Farchive%2F6629988%2Fsouth-viet-nam-mccoys-navy%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Etold%20TIME%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%201966.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BUsually%2C%20depending%20on%20the%20missions%2C%20with%205%2C000%20rockets%2C%20we%20could%20go%20through%20them%20in%20a%20week%2C%20or%20we%20could%20go%20through%20them%20in%20three%20days.%26quot%3B%20Chris%20Page%2C%20a%20crewman%20who%20sailed%20on%20the%20White%20River%20in%20Vietnam%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DGtzZVmbUHGg%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erecalled%3C%2Fa%3E.%20%26quot%3BIt%20just%20depends%20how%20many%20missions%20we%20had%20to%20shoot.%20But%20usually%2C%20at%20the%20longest%2C%20it%20would%20be%20seven%20days%20and%20we'd%20be%20back%20again%20loading%20them.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat%20arsenal%2C%20and%20White%20River's%20ability%20to%20stay%20on%20station%20for%20days%2C%20was%20a%20godsend%20to%20allies%20and%20a%20death%20sentence%20for%20enemies.%20On%20January%2027%2C%201969%2C%20responding%20to%20a%20call%20for%20help%20by%20ARVN%20soldiers%20after%20an%20attack%20on%20VC%20positions%20in%20Qu%E1%BA%A3ng%20Ng%C3%A3i%20province%20resulted%20in%2015%20friendly%20KIAs%2C%20White%20River%20unleashed%20a%20two-hour%20bombardment%20that%20destroyed%2024%20structures%20and%20started%20five%20secondary%20fires.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20day%20later%2C%20White%20River%20blasted%20a%20VC%20staging%20area%20half%20a%20mile%20away%2C%20killing%2015%20VC%20and%20destroying%2063%20more%20structures%20(including%20nine%20bunkers)%20and%2035%20meters%20of%20trails.%20A%20day%20after%20that%2C%20White%20River%20fired%20on%20a%20nearby%20VC%20anti-aircraft%20site%2C%20destroying%20it%20and%20killing%20or%20wounding%2011%20guerillas.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhite%20River%20was%20even%20deadlier%20with%20the%20assistance%20of%20aerial%20spotters.%20While%20supporting%20Australian%20soldiers%20in%20Phuoc%20Tuy%20Province%20from%20October%2022-27%2C%20the%20ship%20destroyed%2097%20structures%20and%20two%20weapons%20sites%20that%20triggered%2013%20secondary%20explosions%2C%20resulting%20in%20at%20least%2018%20VC%20killed%20and%2017%20wounded.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhite%20River's%20last%20mission%2C%20on%20March%2017%2C%201970%2C%20saw%20it%20sail%2018%20miles%20upriver%20into%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.usni.org%2Fmagazines%2Fproceedings%2F1968%2Fapril%2Frung-sat-special-zone-vietnams-mekong-delta%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ERung%20Sat%20Special%20Zone%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20the%20Mekong%20Delta%20%E2%80%94%20then%20the%20deepest%20penetration%20inland%20of%20a%20naval%20gunfire%20support%20ship.%20Over%20the%20course%20of%20five%20hours%2C%20it%20fired%202%2C526%20rockets.%20Thick%20swamp%20and%20foliage%20prevented%20a%20full%20damage%20assessment%2C%20but%20at%20least%2010%20secondary%20fires%20were%20seen%20burning.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20rocket%20tail%20was%20seen%20as%20the%20USS%20Clarion%20River%20fired%20on%20North%20Vietnamese%20positions%20in%201967.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F66e1b43ca0ff598b26668014%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221617%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20rocket%20tail%20was%20seen%20as%20the%20USS%20Clarion%20River%20fired%20on%20North%20Vietnamese%20positions%20in%201967.%3Cp%3EAirman%20R.E.%20Winstead%2FNational%20Archives%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22b9496c86-9655-4c57-b921-43b0b9f0fa57%5C%22%3EFuture%20shore%20bombardment%20and%20LSMs%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EDespite%20its%20value%20and%20firepower%2C%20by%201970%2C%20White%20River%20was%20showing%20its%20age.%20It%20was%20ultimately%20deemed%20unfit%20for%20service%20that%20May%20and%20decommissioned%20and%20stricken%20from%20the%20Naval%20Vessel%20Register.%20The%20following%20November%2C%20the%20ship%20was%20sold%20for%20scrap.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20decades%20since%20White%20River's%20service%2C%20the%20Navy%20has%20largely%20replaced%20naval%20guns%20and%20rockets%20with%20cruise%20missiles%20and%20airstrikes%20from%20carriers%20as%20the%20service%20moved%20towards%20precision%20strikes%2C%20with%20less%20emphasis%20on%20volume%20of%20fire.%20In%20fact%2C%20with%20the%20decommissioning%20of%20the%20battleship%20USS%20Missouri%20in%201992%2C%20no%20gun%20on%20any%20ship%20in%20the%20US%20Navy%20is%20larger%20than%205%20inches%20(a%20reference%20to%20the%20gun%20barrel's%20diameter).%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20role%20of%20shore%20bombardment%20and%20naval%20gun%20support%20more%20broadly%20was%20supposed%20to%20be%20handed%20over%20to%2032%20Zumwalt-class%20destroyers%2C%20each%20of%20which%20would%20be%20equipped%20with%20two%206-inch%20guns%20of%20the%20Advanced%20Gun%20System%20capable%20of%20firing%20Long-Range%20Land%20Attack%20Projectiles%3Cu%3E%3A%3C%2Fu%3E%20rocket-assisted%20precision%20155mm%20rounds%20that%20were%20envisioned%20to%20glide%20out%20to%20targets%20up%20to%2080%20miles%20away.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20development%20issues%20and%20cost%20overruns%20on%20the%20ships%20proved%20cost%20prohibitive%2C%20so%20much%20so%20that%20the%20planned%20order%20of%2032%20ships%20was%20reduced%20to%20just%20three.%20Consequently%2C%20the%20cost%20of%20the%20guided%20gliding%20shells%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.defensenews.com%2Fnaval%2F2018%2F04%2F19%2Fadvanced-gun-system-was-holding-back-the-navys-new-stealth-destroyer%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ejumped%20to